# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillization-of-japanese
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Volume 1 of the Association of Radio Industries and Businesses (ARIB) STD-B24 standard for Broadcast Markup Language specifies, amongst other details, a character encoding for use in Japanese-language broadcasting.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] The latest revision is version 6.3 as of 2016-07-06.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] It includes a number of **ARIB extended characters** (ARIB外字, *ARIB gaiji*) not found in the base standards (JIS X 0208 and JIS X 0201).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] It was the source standard for many symbol characters which were added to Unicode, including portions of the Miscellaneous Symbols, Enclosed Alphanumeric Supplement and Enclosed Ideographic Supplement blocks.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Its contributions partially overlap the Unicode emoji, but were added a year earlier, in Unicode 5.2.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Fascicle 1 of the ARIB STD-B62 standard, published in 2014, defines Unicode mappings for a selection of the B24 extended characters (excluding, for example, those duplicated by JIS X 0213), as well as a few extended Kanji.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] It also includes a mapping of utilised characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane to the BMP's private use area.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] The ARIB STD B24 standard defines multiple character sets and a method of switching between them.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] These include a Kanji set (an extension of JIS X 0208), an Alphanumeric set, a Hiragana set, Katakana sets of two distinct layouts and four mosaic sets.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] This is a double-byte character set extending JIS X 0208.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] The encoding bytes correspond to the row or cell number plus 0x20, or 32 in decimal (see below).
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Hence, the code set starting with 0x21 has a row number of 1, and its cell 1 has a continuation byte of 0x21 (or 33), and so forth.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Most of the code corresponds to JIS X 0208.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] This part is the source standard for a small number of CJK Unified Ideographs in Unicode, where it is designated with the `JARIB-` source prefix in the Unihan database.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] The remainder of the extensions are listed in both table 7-4 (the double-byte code chart) and table 7-10.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Additions from table 7-10 not in table 7-4.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Characters from ARIB STD-B24 which were not retained in ARIB STD-B62 are shown shaded.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] Most of ARIB STD-B24 Mosaic Set D does not exist in Unicode.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/arib-std-b24-character-set] In addition to the modified ISO 2022 encoding, the B24 standard also specifies a Shift JIS encoding following JIS X 0208:1997, but with the addition of the extended characters in the kanji set.
[src:cyrillization-of-japanese/cyrillization-of-japanese] This can be done in an ad hoc fashion (e.g. when "sushi" is transliterated as "суши" in Russian Cyrillic) or using one of a number of systems.
